transcript.text: Hello and welcome to on Print shop.
In today's video we'll understand a few things about the Indesign template creation process.
So for that I will show you the required files to create templates using Indesign.
In this video we have taken an example of a two page flyer product in which all the texts and vector shapes are editable so you can change the color and replace the images.
The design we create here should be such that it can be later uploaded to the Onprintshop solution for creating a template there.
Therefore, after creating the design, you need to ensure that all the used files such as images, logos or any other file should be linked.
Once you access the links panel from the right hand side or the window menu and select the link option in the link panel, you can see that all the image files are linked here.
Kindly take note that if you are working with any design and if they are not linked then after saving the Indesign file, it will not generate the proper preview.
To get a better understanding of the same, let's take an example of a design where the elements are not linked.
Here the image used in the design is not linked.
So when we export this design, it will not give a proper preview.
However, to avoid this error, select the image from the link panel, right click on it and select the Relink option.
You will get the option to select the image and once selected, the missing link icon will be removed and you can adjust your image.
Now let's talk about the format in which you need to save the file.
The most preferable format is a package.
To do so, navigate to the File menu and select Package.
From here you will get the basic summary that which information Indesign will take to generate the package.
So package what package does is it collects the used fonts, images and other files that have been used in the created design and it will be combined into a single package folder.
Before creating the package, make sure that the design you are working on is saved in your system.
Now click on the package button and give a proper path where you want to save the package file.
Yeah, it will add a folder suffix automatically.

Finally, click on the package button and then OK, you can verify that on the given path a package folder has been created consisting of 1 IDML file, 1 Indesign, one PDF file, 1 folder of fonts you have used in your design and the links folder with all the used images.
So this is how you can export the Indesign file and further use it to create a Studio template.
Please note that in the template creation the Designer Studio will support raster such as JPG, JPEG, PNG, TIF and TIF formats and for the vector it will support SVG and PDFs.
This will be all about how you can link the elements in the Indesign template and export them in package format to create the Indesign template in the on Print shop solution.
If you have any questions our support executives are here to help.
Just reach out through live chat on on printshop.com.
Thanks for tuning in.
